   "source": [
    "# `for` Loops\n",
    "\n",
    "## Iterating over Lists and Sequences"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "for i in [0, 1, 2, 3]:\n",
    "    print(i)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 1,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "0\n",
      "1\n",
      "2\n",
      "3\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "for i in range(4):\n",
    "    print(i)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Iterating over Lists and Sequences with Indices\n",
    "\n",
    "In case you want to iterate over a list or sequence of values in and you need to have access to the index of each element, you could do the following:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 2,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "0 4\n",
      "1 3\n",
      "2 2\n",
      "3 1\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "values = range(4, 0, -1)\n",
    "for idx in range(len(values)):\n",
    "    print(idx, values[idx])"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "However, **do not do it as shown above**! First, it is more complicated and second, it is not \"Pythonic\". Instead do the following:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 3,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "0 4\n",
      "1 3\n",
      "2 2\n",
      "3 1\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "for idx, value in enumerate(range(4, 0, -1)):\n",
    "    print(idx, value)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Checking Lists for Element Containment"
   ]
